<br>
Tose led the rotation and was its greatest champion for a long time. In the past, whenever ToN has wanted to do RoV, they have asked us first even when all the dragons were dead. In fact, Tose asked Khary (one of ToN's officers and the sweetest hobbit ever to grace Norrath) to log the conversation many weeks back when we had cleared NToV and they wanted to do RoV. By going that far in verifying that Isengard did not plan to do RoV, he set the precedent that doing RoV without consent of the rotation guild was wrong. <br>
<br>
We have attempted RoV twice, On both those occasions when we planned to do it during our week, ToN said 'ok' and left RoV alone because they understood it was part of the rotation. <br>
<br>
&quot;NToV&quot; is everything from Aary and back. The NToV agreement specifically excludes Eashen, Ikitiar, and Sontalak (though oftentimes rotation guilds kill these to clear their way in or out), it makes no such exclusion for Ring of Vulak. You have to clear NToV to do RoV or else the Lord and Ladies will add during the fight. We cleared NToV, finishing at 1 AM EST or so last night so that we would have a fast clear to RoV tonight. <br>
<br>
But this time, ToN didn't ask. They just went. When contacted about it, and after an hour's long conversation between the guilds, Tose said they (ToN) had not been in the rotation for &quot;months&quot; and are not bound by its rules, that they didn't know it was our week, and that if he had been running the raid he would have asked but a member was running it and forgot. Further Tose said that ToN dropped from the rotation so they they could farm RoV whenever they want. <br>
<br>
First, ToN dropped from the rotation on July 12, 2003 - that's not months. Second, Tose emailed out the schedule governing this week before he stepped down as rotation leader so he had an easy way to find out whose week it was. In fact, its Tose's own post setting out this schedule that is pinned at the top of this forum for easy reference.  Third, as a GL, it is your responsibility to make sure your raid leaders are doing what they should be doing.  <br>
<br>
(Logs and or screenshots of the entire conversation are available if needed)<br>
<br>
Dropping from the rotation should not also drop the tradition, the precedent, that has been standard between our guilds for so long. That if it was Isengard's week in NToV, you ask first before doing RoV because its our rotation week.  If you never thought there was anything wrong with just going and taking it, you would not have required your officers in the past to get a log of Isengard saying &quot;We are passing on RoV this week&quot;.  By your past actions, by every past precedent that has been set between our guilds, RoV is ours to do during our NToV week (which ends tomorrow midnight) unless we tell you we forfeit it. <br>
<br>
The argument that you left the rotation so now you can do whatever you want and whenever you want in NToV will break the rotation. To me, it is a sad thing coming from the person who championed the agreement for so long.  You upheld it when it served you and now you say its meaningless. Nice situatutional ethics. <br>
